commText: Saha and Shubman Gill are at the crease. Saha is on strike. Khaleel Ahmed will open the attack
Khaleel Ahmed to Saha, wide, .. a horror start from Khaleel, looks for the awayswinger and sprays it miles wide of off, called as a wide as Pant moved across and in front of 1st slip to make the stop
Khaleel Ahmed to Saha, no run, much better from Khaleel - on a good length and nipping away with the angle, draws Saha into a loose poke and beats him on the outside edge
Khaleel Ahmed to Saha, no run, fuller length delivery at the stumps, pushed off the front-foot and straight to the fielder at mid-on
Khaleel Ahmed to Saha, no run, on a length and angling across the right-hander, Saha plays with soft hands and can't beat backward point with the dab
Khaleel, from round the wicket
Khaleel Ahmed to Saha, leg byes, 1 run, short of a good length and angling into the thigh-pad, past Saha's flick and rolled to the on-side off the pad
Back to over the wicket for Shubman Gill

Khaleel Ahmed to Shubman Gill, FOUR, lovely, oevrpitched and at the pads, Gill leans across, lets the ball come and then caresses the on-drive through mid-wicket, sublime timing and the ball races away to the ropes

Khaleel Ahmed to Shubman Gill, no run, short of a good length and just outside off - Gill is caught in two minds and makes a late call to play, off the face of the bat and the ball bounces through to the keeper
Ishant Sharma to share the new ball, one slip in place
Ishant Sharma, right-arm fast medium, comes into the attack
Ishant to Saha, 1 run, on a good length and angling into the pads, tucked behind square on the on-side for a single
Ishant to Shubman Gill, no run, fuller length delivery and well wide of off, Gill creams the drive and finds the fielder at mid-off
Ishant to Shubman Gill, no run, rush of blood from Gill - runs down the wicket, makes room and looks to slap it over cover, beaten on the outside edge
Ishant to Shubman Gill, FOUR, short, wide and four, width on offer and Gill went with hard hands on the front-foot drive, was in the air, but he also found the gap square past cover-point
Ishant to Shubman Gill, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Ishant to Shubman Gill, out Caught by Prithvi Shaw!! Ishant has his man now, keeps it full and just outside off - Gill's feet hardly moved as he shaped for the drive, skewed off the outer half and it's straight to cover, Shaw with the simple catch and the Capitals have struck early. Only the 3rd single digit score in 16 IPL innings for Gill at Ahmedabad.

Ishant to Sai Sudharsan, wide, fuller length delivery and angling away from the left-hander, past the tramline and is called as a wide
Ishant to Sai Sudharsan, no run, shout for LBW, but Ishant is bowling from round the wicket and the angle would've taken the ball down leg - Sudharsan was shuffling across on the flick and missed

Khaleel Ahmed to Saha, 1 run, fuller length delivery and angling across the right-hander - Saha closed the face of the bat as he looked to flick, gets a soft leading edge, to cover's left and he's off for a single
A wide slip and a gully in place
Khaleel Ahmed to Sai Sudharsan, 1 run, back of a length and just outside off, dropped into the gap wide of cover for a single
Khaleel Ahmed to Saha, leg byes, 1 run, short of a good length and down leg, Saha was looking to help it on its way and missed, off the thigh-pad and rolled to the on-side
Khaleel Ahmed to Sai Sudharsan, no run, tad fuller and just outside off, looked like it stopped onto the left-hander - Sai Sudharsan checks his forward prod and defends it to the off-side
GT opening Partnership this IPL season \nSudharsan & Gill - Inns: 2, Runs: 118, Avg: 59.0. RR: 8.23, HS: 64 \nSaha & Gill - Inns: 5, Runs: 135, Avg: 27.0, RR: 8.52, HS: 36

Khaleel Ahmed to Sai Sudharsan, FOUR, beautifully played, back of a length and just outside off - Sai Sudharsan stands tall and merely punches it to the left of cover-point - Shaw is slow on the dive and can't make the stop, the timing is sweet and the ball runs away to the ropes
Khaleel Ahmed to Sai Sudharsan, FOUR, gorgeous, a wide half-volley from Khaleel - Sai Sudharsan leans into the drive, head on top of the bounce and then creams it through extra-cover, no one moved
First change, Mukesh Kumar replaces Ishant
Mukesh Kumar, right-arm medium, comes into the attack
Mukesh Kumar to Saha, no run, fuller length delivery on off, pushed back at the bowler
Mukesh Kumar to Saha, leg byes, 1 run, short of a good length and angling into the right-hander, Saha swipes across the line and misses, off the body and rolls to the off-side for a leg-bye

Mukesh Kumar to Sai Sudharsan, 2 runs, a checked drive from Sai Sudharsan, the ball popped in the air and went wide of mid-on - was the slower ball and the left-hander was early into the shot, might've held onto the pitch as well

Mukesh Kumar to Sai Sudharsan, no ball, short of a good length and around off, Sai Sudharsan leans across and turns it to the on-side. It's a front-foot no-ball as well and Sai Sudharsan will get to face a free-hit
Mukesh Kumar to Sai Sudharsan, 1 run, the wide yorker from Mukesh, Sai Sudharsan reaches out on the drive and mistimes it back past the bowler for a single
Mukesh Kumar to Saha, THATS OUT!! Bowled!!

Mukesh Kumar to Saha, out Bowled!! Dragged on! Saha never got going and his innings ends with an ugly mow towards mid-wicket - was through with the shot early and drags a thick inside edge, crashing and sending the middle-stump rolling onto the ground. Almost the perfect start for the Capitals after they opted to field first. Saha b Mukesh Kumar 2(10)
Saha's scores this IPL 19 (15) vs MI 21 (17) vs CSK 25 (13) vs SRH 11 (13) vs PBKS 2 (10) vs DC* - 78 runs at 15.6 average
David Miller, left handed bat, comes to the crease
Mukesh Kumar to Miller, no run, back of a length and well wide of off, Miller went hard on the cut and mistimed it to backward point
A direct hit at the bowler's end, Sai Sudharsan was scrambling home with the dive, has it saved him? No, he's OUT by a couple of yards and the Titans slip further into trouble
Ishant Sharma [1.0-0-6-1] is back into the attack
Ishant to Sai Sudharsan, THATS OUT!! Run Out!!

Ishant to Sai Sudharsan, out Sai Sudharsan Run Out!! A direct hit at the bowler's end, Sai Sudharsan was scrambling home with the dive, has it saved him? No, he's OUT by a couple of yards and the Titans slip further into trouble. Not sure if it was a good call, but it was Sai Sudharsan's call and he has no one but himself to blame, was on the back-foot as he punched one to the right of mid-wicket and set-off - Sumit was quick on the ball, it bounces nicely into his right hand, he then runs forward and throws down the stumps with an under-arm shy, catching Sudharsan well short. Sai Sudharsan run out (Sumit Kumar) 12(9) [4s-2]
First time Sai Sudharsan has dismissed below 30 runs in this IPL
Abhinav Manohar, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Ishant to Miller, no run, on a good length and around the off-stump channel, defended to the on-side
Ishant to Miller, 2 runs, back of a length and angling into the pads, tucked behind square on the on-side and Miller is quick to come back for the second
Ishant to Miller, no run, on a good length and just outside off, defended to the off-side
First time GT lost more than 2 wickets inside powerplay this season
Ishant to Miller, no run, length ball angling into the left-hander, Miller plays with soft hands and gets an inside edge onto his pads
DC have reviewed
Ishant to Miller, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Ishant to Miller, out Caught by Pant!! A loud shout for caught behind, it did deviate off something, the umpire isn't interested and DC have reviewed. Miller was opened up by the angle, but did it come off his thigh-pad? Looks close, but Miller is already walking. UltraEdge is taking its time and there's a clear spike when the ball is next to the bat. The 3rd umpire checks for a clean catch, it's wonderfully held by Pant and GT have lost their 4th wicket. They're falling like nine pins at the moment - short of a good length and angling into the left-hander, Miller was shaping to to work it onto the on-side, the angle opened him up, gets a thin inside edge onto the thigh-pad - the ball flew to Pant's left, he dived full stretch, gets his left palm and completes a superb catch. Miller c Pant b Ishant 2(6)
Rahul Tewatia, left handed bat, comes to the crease
Khaleel Ahmed [2.0-0-15-0] is back into the attack
Khaleel Ahmed to Abhinav Manohar, no run, back of a length and just outside off - Manohar stays back and pushes it to the off-side
Khaleel Ahmed to Abhinav Manohar, no run, on a good length and just outside off, Manohar leans well forward on the defensive push

Khaleel Ahmed to Abhinav Manohar, no run, length ball angling into the pads, Manohar was looking to flick and missed, brushed the pad on its way to the keper - Khaleel is interested, but Pant shakes his head
Khaleel Ahmed to Abhinav Manohar, no run, on a good length and just outside off, Manohar leans across and then inside halves the push back at the bowler
Khaleel Ahmed to Abhinav Manohar, no run, yorker length delivery outside off, Manohar plays with an open face and squeezes it to backward point
Khaleel Ahmed to Abhinav Manohar, no run, fuller length delivery outside off, Manohar saw the width and went with hard hands on the drive, beaten on the outside edge - a maiden over from Khaleel

Mukesh Kumar to Rahul Tewatia, wide, banged in short and rising onto the left-hander, Tewatia was shaping for the pull and is undone by the bounce. It's not called as a wide, GT review and it's a good review, the ball was clearly well over his head

Mukesh Kumar to Rahul Tewatia, no run, short of a good length and well wide of off, Tewatia throws his bat on the cut and missed
Four wickets were lost inside PP this IPL MI vs RR, Wankhede DC vs KKR, Vizag GT vs DC, Ahmedabad*
Mukesh Kumar to Rahul Tewatia, 1 run, fuller length delivery on the pads, flicked in front of square on the on-side for a single
Mukesh Kumar to Abhinav Manohar, no run, short of a good length and on off, Manohar rides the bounce and defends it back at the bowler
Mukesh Kumar to Abhinav Manohar, no run, on a good length and just outside off, pushed off the back-foot to mid-off
Mukesh Kumar to Abhinav Manohar, 2 runs, short of a length and at the pads, Manohar beats mid-wicket with the flick and comes back for the second

Kuldeep Yadav to Abhinav Manohar, 1 run, Kuldeep tosses one on middle and leg, Manohar leans across and works it past mid-wicket for a single
Kuldeep Yadav to Rahul Tewatia, 1 run, tossed up just outside off, pushed into the gap wide of point for a single
Kuldeep Yadav to Abhinav Manohar, 1 run, the wrong 'un from Kuldeep, not sure Manohar read it as he jabbed forward, hit high on the bat and rolled to the off-side

Kuldeep Yadav to Rahul Tewatia, no run, almost another run-out, Abhinav Manohar was a long way down the pitch as he looked for a single, sent back by Tewatia and he's lucky that the return isn't great - Tewatia was on the back-foot as he pushed one towards short third man

Kuldeep Yadav to Rahul Tewatia, no run, beaten, turn and bounce for Kuldeep, drifts in and then spins away, drags the left-hander forward and then beats the push, Pant is quick to break the stumps and the 3rd umpire has a look - the foot is grounded, there's no outside edge and Tewatia survives- NOT OUT is the call
Tristan Stubbs, right-arm off break, comes into the attack
Tristan Stubbs to Abhinav Manohar, no run, tossed up on off, Manohar prods forward and gets an inside edge to the on-side
Tristan Stubbs to Abhinav Manohar, FOUR, hammered, Manohar comes down the pitch, takes the ball on the full and then drills the drive back past the bowler, races away to the straight boundary
Stubbs, from round the wicket
Tristan Stubbs to Abhinav Manohar, THATS OUT!! Stumped!!

Tristan Stubbs to Abhinav Manohar, out Stumped!! Sharp work from Pant and he reckons he's got Manohar here. Did the right-hander drag his foot out? Was beaten by the slider, angled across his meek push and past the outside edge - Pant is quick to break the stumps, Manohar was dragging his feet back, but it's on the line when the zing bails lit up - OUT and the Titans have lost their 5th wicket. The part-time off-spin of Stubbs causing further damage and misery to the Titans - drifted with the angle and beat a tentative push from Manohar. They've taken the strategic break at the fall of the fifth wicket. Abhinav Manohar st Pant b Tristan Stubbs 8(14) [4s-1]
The Titans have activated their super sub - Shahrukh Khan replaces Sai Sudharsan
Shahrukh Khan, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Tristan Stubbs to Shahrukh Khan, no run, tossed up on off, pushed back at the bowler
Tristan Stubbs to Shahrukh Khan, THATS OUT!! Stumped!!

Tristan Stubbs to Shahrukh Khan, wide, out Stumped!! Stubbs could have had a second wicket here - Pant is very confident that he's stumped Shahrukh Khan. Looked very clumsy, did he drag himself out of the crease? They're checking for the caught behind first and it's a flat line on UltraEdge. Onto the stumping now - Pant has dropped the ball, but did it go on and fall on the wicket? Or was his gloves that disturbed the stumps first? It's a tough one for the 3rd umpire - he's checking with several replays, Shahrukh Khan is definitely short of his ground and the umpire reckons that there's gap between the glove and the wicket, so it's the ball which has hit the stumps and the super sub falls for a duck. A lucky wicket for the Capitals, but they'll not complain one bit - dragged flat and down leg, Shahrukh was shaping for the pull and the momentum took him out of the crease, Pant couldn't gather it cleanly, but he gets lucky. Shahrukh Khan st Pant b Tristan Stubbs 0(1)

21:09 Local Time, 15:39 GMT: If Pant had an option to choose one day where nothing could possibly go wrong for his side, this might well be it. Of course, they will have to finish the job with the bat, but, gee, the Capitals have been unstoppable in the field. Bowling, fielding, stumping, catching and what not. At the toss, Pant had a slight bit of hesitation before opting to bowl, but his bowlers proved too good for the GT batters who looked clueless on occasions. You could perhaps argue that the pitch is on the slower side with the odd ball keeping low, but majority of the GT batters were victims of their own-decision making and it might eventually hurt their NRR very badly. But before building thoughts on NRR, can DC brush this aside without any hiccups? Back in 15 for their reply...

Tristan Stubbs - Amazing to get wickets, the boys bowled beautifully out there, the seamers started well upfront, our two spinners, they're world-class. I was just trying to hit the wicket, whatever happens happens, but fortunately it worked. I saw him coming down (on the stumping against Shahrukh). I've been bowling to Rishabh at the nets whenever he's batting, hoping that I'll get to bowl by fluke (during the match), I was going towards long-on when I was called up. We have watched enough IPL, there's always a twist, we'll have to start well and tick them off. I called my dad yesterday, he doesn't like the way cricket's going (on it becoming a batter's game), but I think it's the extra player option which has been the reason for the way the game's going (this IPL).
